In 2013 a major supreme court case, the United States v. Windsor, resulted in the Supreme Court striking down part of a law that banned federal recognition of same-sex marriages. Soon after this, another Supreme Court ruling (Obergefell v. Hodges) made same-sex marriage legal throughout the nation. These rulings mean that married same-sex couples are now entitled to the same rights enjoyed by heterosexual married couples. These rights include Social Security benefits, hospital visitation rights, healthcare benefits, and military family benefits. However, despite these advances, LGBT people still have no federal law to protect them from discrimination in housing or employment.

An Aging Population

While the life expectancy of American born in 1900 was less than 50 years, an American born in 2011 can expect to live to age 79. By 2020, older Americans tended to retire earlier, live longer, and exert more political influence. These factors have strained the country’s social welfare system, especially Social Security and Medicare. In 2010, the federal government spent less than $10 billion on social welfare. By 2013, the amount had increased to $1.9 trillion.

With the large baby-boom generation reaching retirement age, the issue of elder care has become critical. Falling birth rates over the past two decades have meant that when the huge population of baby boomers retires, there will not be enough workers to cover their Social Security benefits. Politicians have been debating this impending reality.

In his second term, President Obama called for privatizing Social Security by allowing younger workers to invest some of their earnings in mutual funds. Opponents of this idea doubted whether the economy would grow quickly enough to generate as much as it would cost. Younger workers are now facing the problem of persistent inflation along with a fluctuating stock market and the increasing debt addressed this allotted of funds. Today the debate continues about their future.

TOPIC 12 America in the Twenty-First Century

Coastal areas of the United States will be under threat. If, as many scientists predict, the warming of the atmosphere leads to a rise in sea levels. In low-lying areas of Florida, high tides are already leading to more frequent and severe flooding, especially in cities such as Miami. With Florida heavily dependent on tourism, an increase in sea levels could seriously affect the state’s economy. In Hawaii, there is concern that sea levels, which have been rising for the last 100 years, may accelerate, threatening urban areas.

Global warming has implications far beyond rising seas. The Environmental Protection Agency warns that in Alaska, where the increase in average temperatures is more than twice the warming in the rest of the United States, forest varieties are changing, wild life is decreasing, and temperatures are rising, and permafrost is thawing. This melting permafrost, which may lead to ground subsidence, is in direct threat to transportation routes and buildings.

The Environment and Local Economies

In the West, water is an important environmental and economic issue because it is so scarce. Recent periods of drought in California, with short periods of intense rainfall, have had a dramatic effect on the state’s farming economy.
